Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Haiti. The Haitian authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
The FCO strongly encourage non-resident British nationals in Haiti to consider leaving quickly to avoid difficulties they may face in getting home if travel out of the country and the region are further affected. For information on how to return to the UK from Haiti, see Return to the UK
Entry and borders
On 19 March Haiti announced the closure of all its land, sea and air borders to travellers. Quarantine restrictions of 14 days have been introduced for travellers from affected countries.
Local measures
On 19 March the Haitian President announced a national state of emergency and detailed further measures aimed at tackling the spread of COVID-19. Key measures include:
curfew between 8pm and 5am, effective from Friday 20 March
citizens to stay at home and limit movement to essential only
schools, universities, places of worship and factories to close
a ban on all events/meetings of more than 10 people
Youâ€™re strongly advised to follow these regulations in full.
Information is available from the Ministry of Health (Ministere de la Sante publique et de la Population (in French and Kreyol).
Further information
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
